canonical:
  title: 殤子法源壙銘
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 沙彌法源吾子也捨吾姓而從釋氏者也年十一投禪師規公祝髮爲衲僧事師甚謹性警悟凡使令輒迎導其意不須頤指故師最愛之在寺暴得病至吾家卧一宵明日而化閒三日瘞于山噫何其倐忽也如此歲金龍月黃鍾剃度年水馬律夾鍾反眞爲僧凡一十六月耳予遂爲銘詞刻三尺木板納于壙寓哀而已其身與銘不如速朽何必鑱諸石壽其傳哉銘曰僧其服一日足况二冬一夏汝死猶可
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 殤子法源壙銘
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 沙彌法源。吾子也。捨吾姓而從釋氏者也。年十一。投禪師規公祝髮爲衲僧。事師甚謹。性警悟。凡使令輒迎導其意。不須頤指。故師最愛之。在寺暴得病。至吾家卧一宵。明日而化。閒三日瘞于山。噫何其倐忽也如此。歲金龍月黃鍾剃度。年水馬律夾鍾反眞。爲僧凡一十六月耳。予遂爲銘詞。刻三尺木板納于壙。寓哀而已。其身與銘。不如速朽。何必鑱諸石壽其傳哉。銘曰。僧其服。一日足。况二冬一夏。汝死猶可。
korean:
  title: 상자 법원 광명
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: |-
    어린 중 법원은 내 아들인데, 내 성을 버리고 부처를 따른 자이다. 나이 11세에 선사 규공(規公)을 따라, 머리 깎고 고깔 쓴 중이 되었다. 스승 섬기기를 매우 삼가고 천성이 영민하여 심부름을 시키면 시키는 뜻에 맞게 하므로 문득 그의 생각대로 하여 일일이 지시가 필요 없었다. 그러므로 스승이 제일 사랑하였다. 절에서 갑자기 병이 나서, 내 집에 와서 누은 지 하룻밤 만에 저 세상으로 가고 3일을 지나 산에 묻으니, 아, 어찌도 이렇게 빠르단 말인가. 경진년 11월에 머리깎고 중이 되었다가 임오년 2월에 저 세상으로 돌아가니, 중이 된 지 무릇 16개월이었다. 내가 드디어 명문을 지어 석 자 나무 널에 새겨서 무덤 속에 넣으니, 슬픈 마음을 적는 것일 뿐이다. 그 시체나 명문은 빨리 썩어 없어지는 것만 같지 못한 것이니, 어찌 반드시 돌에 새겨, 오래도록 전하게 할 것인가. 명문에 이르기를,
    중의 그 옷은 하루만 입어도 족한데
    하물며 두 해 겨울, 한해 여름임에랴
    네가 죽은 것이, 오히려 좋은 일이다
    하였다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1250_010_0050&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Epitaph for the Young Monk Beopwon
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The young novice Beopwon was my son, who abandoned my surname to follow the Buddha. At eleven years of age, he shaved his head and donned the robes of a monk under the guidance of Master Gyugong. He served his teacher with utmost reverence, possessed keen wisdom, and whenever given a task, he would anticipate and fulfill his master's wishes without needing a single word of instruction. Thus his teacher cherished him above all others.

    While at the temple, he suddenly fell ill. He came to my home and lay there through one night. By the next morning, he had passed into the other world. Three days later, we buried him in the mountain.

    Alas, how swiftly it came to pass! He received the tonsure in the eleventh month of the Year of the Dragon, and passed away in the second month of the Year of the Horse—a monk for merely sixteen months.

    I have composed this epitaph and carved it upon a wooden tablet three feet long, which I place within his tomb. It merely holds my sorrow. Whether his body or this inscription, both will crumble to dust—neither will endure. Why should I trouble to carve it in stone to prolong its memory?

    The epitaph reads:

    A monk's robes—one day would suffice to wear,
    Much less two winters and one summer's care.
    That you have died is perhaps a mercy rare.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Master Gyugong (規公): The Buddhist teacher under whom young Beopwon became a novice monk.'
  - key: ''
    value: The epitaph's final sentiment reflects a Buddhist perspective on the transience of life and the questionable value of earthly monuments.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gyeong-bo (1168-1241) was one of Korea's greatest medieval scholars and literary figures, serving in high government positions during the Goryeo dynasty.
